## What happened

Starting in .NET 11 (following the deprecation path begun in earlier versions), `DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS. Apple's native crypto library (`Security.framework` / CryptoKit) has **never** implemented DSA, and .NET no longer ships an OpenSSL-based fallback on macOS. Windows (CNG) and Linux (OpenSSL) still support it, which is why only macOS breaks.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not generate new ones), the cleanest fix is to use a **managed (portable) DSA implementation** via **Bouncy Castle**:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

Then replace the platform-dependent call:

```csharp
// ❌ Before — throws on macOS in .NET 11
using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyParams);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);
```

```csharp
// ✅ After — works everywhere (managed code, no native dependency)
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Signers;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Math;

var pubKey = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(
    new BigInteger(1, legacyParams.Y),
    new DsaParameters(
        new BigInteger(1, legacyParams.P),
        new BigInteger(1, legacyParams.Q),
        new BigInteger(1, legacyParams.G)));

var signer = new DsaDigestSigner(new DsaSigner(), new Sha1Digest());
signer.Init(false, pubKey);           // false = verify mode
signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);
```

## Key points

| Option | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| **Bouncy Castle** (recommended) | Fully managed, cross-platform, no native deps | Extra NuGet dependency |
| Install OpenSSL on macOS + `DOTNET_SYSTEM_NET_SECURITY_OPENSSL=1` | No code changes | Fragile CI/deployment, not officially supported |
| Drop macOS support | Zero effort | Loses a platform |

Since you're only doing **legacy verification** (not new signing), Bouncy Castle is the right call — it keeps all three platforms working with zero native dependencies, and you can migrate away from DSA signatures over time.
